{"experiment_name": "env-buffer-limits-sweep", "timestamp": "2026-03-12T21:30:00+00:00", "resolution": 1024, "search_area": "runtime-config", "verdict": "KEEP (env var recommendation)", "fidelity_passed": true, "median_ms": 437.3, "p95_ms": 446.7, "peak_memory_mb": 1407.4, "notes": "exp29: MLX_MAX_MB_PER_BUFFER=2 MLX_MAX_OPS_PER_BUFFER=2 gives 58% peak memory reduction (3319→1407MB) with no latency penalty. Latency unchanged across all buffer sizes (thermal-controlled A/B test). Memory scales linearly with buffer limits: MB=8→2099MB, MB=16→2709MB, MB=32→3319MB (default), MB=128→4706MB. OPS=2 saves additional 318MB vs default OPS. No code changes — env var only."}
{"experiment_name": "wired-limit-sweep", "timestamp": "2026-03-12T22:15:00+00:00", "resolution": 1024, "search_area": "runtime-config", "verdict": "REVERT", "fidelity_passed": true, "median_ms": 451.33, "p95_ms": 455.8, "peak_memory_mb": 3319.1, "notes": "exp30: mx.set_wired_limit() sweep at 0/512/1024/1536/2048/3072/4096 MB. No benefit at any value. Higher limits INCREASE latency (+5-10%), peak memory (+500-700MB), and variance. wired_limit=0 (default/disabled) is optimal. Hypothesis disproven — pinning weights in physical RAM hurts unified memory performance on Apple Silicon."}
{"experiment_name": "fidelity-budget-audit", "timestamp": "2026-03-12T22:45:00+00:00", "resolution": 1024, "search_area": "fidelity-analysis", "verdict": "AUDIT (informational)", "fidelity_passed": true, "median_ms": null, "p95_ms": null, "peak_memory_mb": null, "notes": "exp31: Bisected bf16 conversions for error contribution @1024. Current headroom: alpha=23.3%, fg=8.2% (critical). Top contributors: (1) backbone-bf16 contributes 21.3% of fg_final error — disabling raises fg headroom 8.2%->27.8%. (2) refiner-bf16 contributes 52.2% of alpha_final error but only 6.5% of fg_final. (3) decoder-bf16 contributes 5.0% alpha, 7.6% fg. Recommendation: if fg headroom becomes blocking, revert backbone_bf16_stages123 first — recovers 19.6% fg headroom with minimal latency cost. Refiner bf16 is safe to keep (alpha-dominated error). All-fp32 baseline: alpha=0.002, fg=0.006 (95%+ headroom)."}
{"experiment_name": "groupnorm-native-mode", "timestamp": "2026-03-12T23:00:00+00:00", "resolution": 1024, "search_area": "kernel-optimization", "verdict": "REVERT", "fidelity_passed": false, "median_ms": 427.8, "p95_ms": 434.05, "peak_memory_mb": 3319.1, "notes": "exp32: Dropping pytorch_compatible=True from refiner GroupNorm. CATASTROPHIC fidelity failure: alpha_final=0.987, fg_final=0.973 (vs 0.050 threshold). Native MLX GroupNorm computes different normalization statistics — non-zero group means vs PyTorch's zero-mean guarantee. Not a weight permutation issue; fundamentally different reduction axes. Coarse outputs (pre-refiner) unaffected, confirming error is 100% from refiner GN. No weight remap can fix this. pytorch_compatible=True is REQUIRED for correctness."}
